homework.funcAn.final

1 Overview

In this script, we will perform functional analysis of the identified, differential genes.

In the first part, we will do over-representation analysis (ORA).

In the second part, we will do functional class scoring using gene set enrichement analysis (GSEA).

inpDir <- paste(getwd(), "../009_DESeq2clean/all_vs_GM", sep = "/")

Rat2Mouse_CHIP <- read_delim("../000_referenceseq/CHIP/Rat_Ensembl_Gene_ID_Mouse_Orthologs_MSigDB.v2023.2.Mm.chip", 
    delim = "\t", escape_double = FALSE, 
    trim_ws = TRUE)
#View(Rat2Mouse_CHIP)

2.2.2 convert to dataframe and merge with results from differential expression analysis

The next step is to know in which genset each of the genes tested for differential regulation belongs to. Therefore, we generate a table, with two columns, one geneset, and one gene-symbol column.

First convert GeneSetCollection Object into a list.

l_gs <- geneIds(gmt_r)

Then convert it into a data.frame using functions from the tidyverse universe tidyverse

df_gsToGene <- as.data.frame(unnest(enframe(l_gs, 
                                            name = "geneset", 
                                            value = "symbol"), 
                                    cols = "symbol"))
dim(df_gsToGene)
## [1] 70591     2
sum(duplicated(df_gsToGene$symbol))
## [1] 61546
length(unique(df_gsToGene$symbol))
## [1] 9045
head(df_gsToGene, n=4)
  • Many genes are present in multiple pathways, therefore, much more rows than unique genes. Note that number of unique genes in Reactome is far less than number of unique genes tested for differential expression analysis (9045 vs.~17500).

2.3 extract unique genes from Reactome, und use to subset result from diff.exp.analysis

The genes in the Reactome database are our universe, within we try to find an association between the gensets and our differentially expressed genes. Subset results of differentially expressed genes to genes present in Reactome database.

v_gInR <- unique(df_gsToGene$symbol)

Before subsetting, we check if we have duplicated gene symbols in our result tables

2.4 next code cell orthologue maps rat genes to the mouse orthologues

df_DM.vs.GM.noNa$symbolmouse <- Rat2Mouse_CHIP$"Gene Symbol"[match(df_DM.vs.GM.noNa$ENSEMBLEID, Rat2Mouse_CHIP$"Probe Set ID")]
sum(duplicated(df_DM.vs.GM.noNa$symbolmouse))

Show rows with duplicated gene symbols

df_DM.vs.GM.noNa[duplicated(df_DM.vs.GM.noNa$symbolmouse) | 
                 duplicated(df_DM.vs.GM.noNa$symbolmouse, fromLast=T), ]

We see that there are some genes with multiple Ensemble Gene Ids.

We simply remove one of the duplicates randomly, to avoid problems later, with subsetting, merging, 

df_DM.vs.GM.noNa <- df_DM.vs.GM.noNa[!duplicated(df_DM.vs.GM.noNa$symbolmouse), ]
# consistency check, should be 0 afterwards
sum(duplicated(df_DM.vs.GM.noNa$symbolmouse))
## [1] 0

Next, we subset the data.

# already use mouse symbols instead of rat symbols
df_DM.vs.GM.noNa <- df_DM.vs.GM.noNa[df_DM.vs.GM.noNa$symbolmouse %in% v_gInR, ]

Not all of the 9045 genes in the Reactome Database were expressed in our data. We end up with ~ 6150 genes, that were expressed, and that are in the Reactome database.

2.4.3 Check how the overlap between sig. genes and reactome hemostasis genset is

Do it just for DM vs GM

tab <- table(df_DM.vs.GM.noNa$isSig, 
             df_DM.vs.GM.noNa$isHemostasis)
tab_sum <- addmargins(tab, FUN = sum)
## Margins computed over dimensions
## in the following order:
## 1: 
## 2:
tab_sum
##      
##          0    1  sum
##   0   5363  304 5667

In the first row we have the not sig. genes, in the second row the sig. genes, and in the third row we have the sum. In the first column we have the genes that are not in the genset, in the second column we have the genes that are in the genset, and in the third column we have the sum.

2.4.4 Now use Fisher Exact test to test for sig. enrichment of Homeostasis genes in sig. reg. genes

fisher.test(tab)
## 
##  Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data
## 
## data:  tab
## p-value = 0.01421
## alternative hypothesis: true odds ratio is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.080488 2.103148
## sample estimates:
## odds ratio 
##   1.521248

We have a sig. enrichment of homeostasis genes in sig. genes. This is shown by the p-value, but you also have to interpret the odds ratio correctly, to judge if there is an enrichment, or a depletion, of homeostasis genes in the sig. genes.

2.4.5 Manually calculate Odds Ratio

The odds is the ratio of nr. event occurs / nr. event does not occur.

Odds of homeostasis genes in sig. genes: nr. homeostasis genes in sig. genes / nr. not homoestasis genes in sig. genes.

Odds of homeostasis genes in not sig. genes: nr. homeostasis genes in not sig. genes / nr. not homoestasis genes in not sig. genes.

odds_sigG <- 47/545
odds_notSigG <- 304/5363
odds_sigG
## [1] 0.08623853
odds_notSigG
## [1] 0.05668469

higher proportion of homeostasis genes in sig. genes than in not sig. genes.

Now calculate Odds ratio

if odds ratio over 1 than enrichement of geneset, if odds ratio under 1 than depletion of geneset

odds_ratio <- odds_sigG/odds_notSigG
odds_ratio
## [1] 1.521373

2.5.4 run ClusterProfiler for ORA of Reactome genesets

r_res <- enrichPathway(gene=v_DM.vs.GM.sig, 
                   pvalueCutoff = 0.05, 
                   readable=TRUE, # convert EntrezId to Gene symbols in result table
                   organism = "mouse", 
                   universe = v_DM.vs.GM.all)
class(r_res) # enrichResult
## [1] "enrichResult"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "DOSE"

ClusterProfiler does not give you an odds ratio, to judge if geneset is enriched, or depleted. But you can calculate it by deviding GeneRation / BgRatio.

map_dbl(df_res$GeneRatio, ~ eval(parse(text=.x)))/map_dbl(df_res$BgRatio, ~ eval(parse(text=.x)))

2.5.8 show sig. genes in Reactome Pathway illustration

To show fold change in Reactome Pathway illustration, a vector of log2fc of sig. genes, with genes named by Entrezid, is needed.

v_nam <- df_DM.vs.GM.noNa.sig$log2FoldChange
names(v_nam) <- df_DM.vs.GM.noNa.sig$ENTREZID
v_nam[1:4]
##    268860     27421     66885     11482 
## -1.097944  2.062643  1.923718  3.403349

Now plot Reactome pathway Hemostasis.

viewPathway("Activation of Matrix Metalloproteinases", 
            readable = T, 
            foldChange = v_nam, 
            organism = "mouse") +
  scale_color_gradient2(low = "blue", mid = "white", high = "red", midpoint = 0) + labs(color = "Fold Change")

viewPathway("Extracellular matrix organization", 
            readable = T, 
            foldChange = v_nam, 
            organism = "mouse") +
  scale_color_gradient2(low = "blue", mid = "white", high = "red", midpoint = 0) + labs(color = "Fold Change")

Genes up or down-regulated are indicated. Brown circles indicate genes not within sig. genes. Gray lines indicates known interactions.

Here is how the pathway looks in Reactome pathway browser pathwayBrowser.

Note that some of our enriched Pathways are in the hirarchy below Hemostasis. So probably there are similar genes in some of the pathways. Plot heatmap.

heatplot(r_res, foldChange=v_nam, showCategory=12) + scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", mid = "white", high = "red", midpoint = 0) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 1))
